body:
Unpopular opinion

I feel like in order to really appreciate and ship Villaneve, you need to give a shit about Villanelle and Eve.

You can’t ship Villaneve if you don’t care about Eve’s character development. Eve is not a vessel for normalcy and happiness for Villanelle. She’s not a tool for Villanelle. She’s her own character who’s going through the same volatile, eye-opening changes just like Villanelle. Those changes will cause her to clash with Villanelle in ways we might not like but we have to empathize with. 

If you can’t respect nor appreciate that, please stop saying you ship Villaneve.

summary: I've read some people say that Eve deserved to get shot and it just baffles me - did we even watch the same episode? Let's just...
body:
I’ve read some people say that Eve deserved to get shot and it just baffles me - did we even watch the same episode? Let’s just recap what she’s been through in a short time lapse:

- She descovered that Carolyn had been using her all along;

- She discovered that Villanelle manipulated her into KILLING someone, even though she had the means to do it herself;

- Carolyn told her Kenny was part of the clean up mission;

- Hugo was murdered.

Eve was never normal, but differently from Villanelle, she hid her true self from others out of fear of being called “monster” (like The Ghost did), losing her husband and the normalcy of life she struggled to achieve and maintain.

Villanelle, on the other hand, never wanted that normal life and did nothing to hide her psychopathic nature - she comitted felonies and her first murder as a young girl. She learned to blend in after she was trained by Konstantin, with the sole purpose of entering her target’s social circle and making the kill easier and less suspicious.

In the last episode, Villanelle and Eve were considered to be equals - they both killed and lost someone, were betrayed and couldn’t go back to their old lives. However, Eve wasn’t as accepting of her feelings towards Villanelle as the latter was towards her because, like I said before, it’d mean embracing the darkness within her and giving up the normal life she’s built.

Eve was in shock after killing Raymond and got understandably angry and upset when she discovered it was all part of Villanelle’s plan - force Eve to bring forth her darkest side because Villanelle knew they were the same and wanted Eve to realise that.

We spent two seasons watching Eve deny her obsessive love for Villanelle, it’d make no sense for her to just accept it, after going through so much, and run away with Villanelle like nothing happened. Therefore, saying that Eve deserved to get shot is pretty unfair to me.
